# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dr-gray-s-hospital
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Plans for the complex were announced in 2010.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The facility, which cost £15 million to construct, opened in December 2013.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] It was the first healthcare facility to be completed in Scotland under the hub framework of the Scottish Futures Trust.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village, which is designed to offer services to 700 patients a day, contains 275 rooms including three dental suites, two minor procedure rooms and 29 consulting rooms.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Services being run from the health village include: cardiac rehabilitation, dentistry, dietetics, physiotherapy, podiatry, radiology, sexual health, speech and language therapy and minor surgery.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] An endoscopy service was provided from June 2014.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village acts as an educational resource for patients, carers and community-based staff.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village also provides improved access to community based learning opportunities for healthcare professionals such as general practitioners (GPs) and GP trainees.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Work on a mural on the side of the building began in July 2021.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] It is being painted by Fanakapan, a London-based artist, as part of the 2021 NuArt Festival.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital has its origins in the a small facility established at Guestrow in 1870.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] It moved to Barrett's Close in 1893 and to Castle Street in 1900.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The move to a new building, which was designed by James Brown Nicol and built between 1934 and 1937, formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by Professor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] An ante-natal hospital was added in 1941 and the facility joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital progressed to stage two accreditation of the Baby Friendly Hospital Initiative in July 2011.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Construction of new hospital buildings - for The Baird Family Hospital and Anchor cancer centre - was delayed after costs escalated from £163m to £223m.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] In February 2020, forecast completion dates were 2022 and March 2023 respectively.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The Department of Obstetrics and Gynaecology, University of Aberdeen, is based at the hospital, which conducts a variety of research with an emphasis on obstetric epidemiology (including maternal mortality and morbidity), infertility and the prevention of cancer in women.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Aberdeen is also particularly known for its research into multiple pregnancy.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The associated **Dugald Baird Centre for Research on Women's Health** was set up in 1995 and is primarily a research unit, with consultative and teaching responsibilities.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Current work focuses on a number of themes in reproductive health research and methodological development in evaluation.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The centre is named after Sir Dugald Baird (1899–1986), Regius Professor of Midwifery at the University of Aberdeen from 1937 to 1965.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The **Aberdeen Royal Infirmary** (**ARI**) is the largest hospital in the Grampian area, located on the Foresterhill site in Aberdeen, Scotland.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI is a teaching hospital offering tertiary care for a population of over 600,000 across the north-east of Scotland.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] It offers all medical specialities with the exception of heart and liver transplants.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Aberdeen Royal Infirmary has it origins in a facility established at Woolmanhill in 1739.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The move to the current site formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by the Scottish doctor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The granite buildings on the site were designed by James Brown Nicol.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital was officially opened by the Duke and Duchess of York on 23 September 1936—King Edward VIII had been due to open the infirmary but he called off his visit and instead went to Ballater railway station to meet the American socialite Wallis Simpson off her train.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The first patients were admitted a month later.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In the 1980s the English physicist John Mallard led a team which built the first whole body magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) scanner.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The world's first whole-body MRI scanner was used for diagnostic imaging between 1980 and 1983.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The prototype machine, Mark One, was put on display in the hospital's art gallery in February 2016.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Following fundraising by *Evening Express* readers, in 1992 a Siemens scanner costing £870,000 was brought.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1984, a hyperbaric oxygen unit was built for the treatment of decompression illness and the hospital's in vitro fertilisation unit achieved a number of successful pregnancies in 1985, its first year of operation.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1986, a new £550,000 out-patient eye clinic opened, offering corrective laser eye surgery, and in 1989, the hospital introduced a breast cancer screening service for women over the age of 50, with X-rays taken every three years.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2013, a £110m emergency care centre development was completed.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] This was the first time that the Foresterhill campus had hosted emergency and urgent care facilities in the same building, and 75% of the beds in the centre are single-occupancy.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In February 2014, it was revealed that the hospital has a repairs backlog of £60 million.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] On 26 June 2014, John Swinney, the then Finance Secretary, announced a £120 million investment for a new cancer centre and maternity hospital on the site.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2016, the ARI became one of four major trauma centres as part of a national major trauma network in Scotland.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Social workers can be contacted in the hospital, and a branch of the Citizens Advice Bureau is based there.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by the volunteer-run radio station, Grampian Hospital Radio.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by several bus services with regular connections to Aberdeen city centre and service to places as far as Inverurie and Oldmeldrum in the north, Inverness in the West and Cove Bay in the south.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new multistorey carpark with space for over 1,000 cars was opened in 2017.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] There are close links with the University of Aberdeen's medical school and there has been pioneering research in many fields, including the development of MRI and positron emission tomography (PET) scanning.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new PET scanner was installed in 2006.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI has been one of the centres evaluating telemedicine equipment and developing services in Scotland.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Academy of Medical Royal Colleges and Faculties in Scotland produced a report entitled "Learning from serious failings in care" in July 2015.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The investigation was launched after scandals in the health service in 2013 and 2014 leading to concerns about patient safety and care at the infirmary.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] They found leadership and accountability were often lacking and bullying was endemic.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The 20 recommendations for improvements in the NHS included a set of minimum safe staffing levels for consultants, doctors, nurses and other staff in hospital settings.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aboyne-hospital] The facility, which was designed by Jenkins & Marr, opened as an infectious diseases hospital in 1898.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aboyne-hospital] A ward pavilion was added in 1926 and, after the hospital had joined the National Health Service in 1948, a new health centre was added in 1980.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/aboyne-hospital] A major refurbishment started in 2002 and the newly modernised facilities were opened by Anne, Princess Royal in August 2003.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The initiative is a global effort for improving the role of maternity services to enable mothers to breastfeed babies for the best start in life.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] It aims at improving the care of pregnant women, mothers and newborns at health facilities that provide maternity services for protecting, promoting and supporting breastfeeding, in accordance with the International Code of Marketing of Breast-milk Substitutes.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] UNICEF, WHO, and many national government health agencies recommend that babies are breastfed exclusively for their first six months of life.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Studies have shown that breastfed babies are less likely to suffer from serious illnesses, including gastroenteritis, asthma, eczema, and respiratory and ear infections.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Adults who were breastfed as babies may be less likely to develop risk factors for heart disease such as obesity and high blood pressure.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] There are benefits for mothers too: women who don't breastfeed have increased risk of developing heart disease, hypertension, diabetes, high cholesterol, breast cancer, ovarian cancer and hip fractures in later life.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The BFHI aims to increase the numbers of babies who are exclusively breastfed worldwide, a goal which the WHO estimates could contribute to avoiding over a million child deaths each year, and potentially many premature maternal deaths as well.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Comply fully with the International Code of Marketing of Breast-milk Substitutes and relevant World Health Assembly resolutions.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Have a written infant feeding policy that is routinely communicated to staff and parents.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Establish ongoing monitoring and data-management systems.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Ensure that staff have sufficient knowledge, competence and skills to support breastfeeding.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Discuss the importance and management of breastfeeding with pregnant women and their families.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Facilitate immediate and uninterrupted skin-to-skin contact and support mothers to initiate breastfeeding as soon as possible after birth.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Support mothers to initiate and maintain breastfeeding and manage common difficulties.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Do not provide breastfed newborns any food or fluids other than breast milk, unless medically indicated.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Enable mothers and their infants to remain together and to practise rooming-in 24 hours a day.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Support mothers to recognize and respond to their infants' cues for feeding.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Counsel mothers on the use and risks of feeding bottles, teats and pacifiers.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Coordinate discharge so that parents and their infants have timely access to ongoing support and care.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The program also restricts use by the hospital of free formula or other infant care aids provided by formula companies and recommends that when formula is medically needed, it should be given in a small cup or spoon, rather than a bottle and should only be used to supplement breastfeeding.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] As of 2011, approximately 15,000 facilities in more than 152 countries had been inspected and accredited as "Baby-Friendly." The number of accredited hospitals has continued to grow.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] As of 2019, a survey found that 28% of the hospitals in the US were registered as Baby Friendly.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The World Health Organization recommends that if a mother is unable to breastfeed, chooses not to breastfeed, or if her baby (often premature) shows signs that it isn't getting enough breast-milk, a healthy wet nurse or milk from a donor is a healthy alternative to formula.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] A special formula is manufactured for premature babies, although the World Health Organization recommends it only if breast-milk is medically not an option such as if a premature baby has to be fed formula through a tube to maintain a healthy weight.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The World Health Organization advocates the importance of a baby being close to its mother whenever possible even if the mother does not breastfeed.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In Canada, the provinces of Quebec and New Brunswick have mandated the implementation of the BFHI.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] All public health units in Ontario have been required to work towards having BFI designation since 2011.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In 2012, the Ministry of Health and Long Term Care in Ontario added BFI status to their progress indicators for Public Health Units thus requiring all Public Health Units in Ontario to begin implementation of BFI.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Other provinces and territories are implementing strategies at regional and local levels.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] As of 2008, 18 health care facilities (9 hospitals & birthing centres and 9 community health services) had been designated "Baby-Friendly" across the country.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Women's Hospital and Health Centre has been recognized as a breast-feeding and "baby-friendly" hospital by the World Health Organization (WHO) and UNICEF since 2008.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] It is the largest hospital in Canada to receive the designation.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] China, now has more than 6,000 Baby-Friendly Hospitals, exclusive breastfeeding in rural areas rose from 29 per cent in 1992 to 68 per cent in 1994; in urban areas, the increase was from 10 per cent to 48 per cent.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In Cuba, 49 of the country's 56 hospitals and maternity facilities have been designated as "baby-friendly".
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In the six years following the initiation of the BFHI program, the rate of exclusive breastfeeding at four months almost tripled - from 25 per cent in 1990 to 72 per cent in 1996.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In Hong Kong several hospitals have shown interest in being designated Baby Friendly.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] However, only Queen Elizabeth Hospital has advanced past the Award of Level 2 Participation stage and is well on its way to receiving BFHI accreditation.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The BFHI started in Ireland in 1998 under the auspices of the Irish Health Promoting Hospitals Network (a WHO programme).
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The BFHI in Ireland became an independent registered charity in mid-2016 and changed their name to Baby Friendly Health Initiative.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Sweden is considered the global leader in terms of BFHI implementation: four years after the programme was introduced in 1993, all of the then 65 maternity centres in the country had been designated "baby-friendly".
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In 2014 78.60% of babies were born in BFHI hospitals.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Between 2001 and 2013, the increase in certified hospitals was from 38 to 176.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The UNICEF UK Baby Friendly Initiative was launched in the United Kingdom in 1995.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The Initiative works with the National Health Service (NHS) to ensure a high standard of care for pregnant women and breastfeeding mothers and babies in hospitals and community health settings.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The Baby Friendly Initiative accredits health-care facilities that adopt internationally recognised best practice standards for breastfeeding.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] During each stage of accreditation, the Initiative provides support as facilities implement standards relating to policies and procedures, staff education, effective auditing, educating pregnant women and mothers, and other relevant areas.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In 1998, its principles were extended to cover the work of community health-care services with the *Seven Point Plan for the Promotion, Protection and Support of Breastfeeding in Community Health Care Settings*.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] It has been estimated that if all babies were breastfed, over £35m would be saved by the NHS in England and Wales each year in treating gastroenteritis alone.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Despite that, in 2013 breastfeeding rates in the UK were amongst the lowest in Europe: 78 per cent of babies born in the UK were breastfed at birth, falling to 63 per cent at one week.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Only one in five babies still received breastmilk at six months.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In 2013 the success of the initiative in Scotland showed that 90% of Scottish mothers gave birth in a UNICEF-accredited Baby Friendly hospital.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] This compared to 30% of mothers in England, 58% for Wales and 57% in Northern Ireland.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The first hospitals verified as Baby-Friendly in the US were on the Pacific Coast.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The first US hospital to receive this designation was Evergreen Hospital Medical Center, in Kirkland, Washington, which was certified in September 1996.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] All of these early adopters were able to achieve 100% breastfeeding initiation rates.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In New York City, the Harlem Hospital Center was the first hospital to receive the "Baby Friendly" certification granted by Baby-Friendly USA for the city in 2008.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] In 2011, New York University Langone Medical Center became the second hospital to receive the Baby-Friendly Hospital designation in New York City.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The Johns Hopkins Hospital in Maryland describes the process of receiving the Baby Friendly designation.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] As of 2 May 2018, the United States had 512 hospitals that hold the Baby-Friendly designation.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] This translates to 24.57% of annual births.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] As of 2019, 28% of hospitals in the U.S. have been accredited by the WHO.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] One group of authors expressed concerns in a paper published in October 2016.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] It questioned whether full compliance with the ten steps of the initiative might inadvertently lead to the promotion of potentially hazardous practices and/or counterproductive outcomes.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Specific concerns described in this paper included increased risk of sudden unexpected postnatal collapse, rigidly-enforced rooming-in practices leading to exhausted or heavily medicated mothers caring for newborns, and an unnecessary ban on pacifier use.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] A 2016 systematic review examined the impact of BFHI implementation on breastfeeding and child health outcomes worldwide and in the United States.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The authors suggested that following the BFHI Ten Steps had a positive impact on short, medium, and long-term breastfeeding outcomes.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] However, they warned their results for the United States explaining "All of the United States BFHI evidence comes from observational studies, the vast majority of which are of very low or low quality.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Although there is consistent empirical evidence that BFHI has led to improvements in breastfeeding outcomes in the very short and short terms, its impact on BF outcomes in the long term remains unclear".
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Looking at 58 studies, the review found that community support was the key to long-term sustainability of breastfeeding that was initiated in the BFHI hospital setting.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] A study published in the *Journal of Pediatrics* in 2019 showed that increased rates of implementation of the BFHI were temporally associated with a decrease in the rate of infant deaths in the first six days after birth.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The authors said that their findings dispelled the suggestion that hospital-based breastfeeding initiatives might increase infant death from asphyxiation.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The authors did not discuss the other potential harms to mother and baby that critics have raised, such as increased incidence of neonate hospital admission due to dehydration and poor maternal mental health outcomes.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] A 2017 study focusing on hospital readmission among infants based on method of feeding raised concerns that exclusive breastfeeding is linked to double the rate of readmission to hospital among neonates as compared to formula feeding.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Critics of the Baby Friendly Initiative point to this type of data and several anecdotal stories of babies harmed at hospitals following the Baby Friendly Initiative as evidence that the current guidelines are potentially harmful and not meeting the needs of mother or baby.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] A 2021 review of systematic reviews raised further doubts about some of the claims raised in support of the Baby Friendly Initiative, as it was found that the majority of cited studies concluding benefits of implementation were of low or very low quality.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] The authors raised a number of concerns surrounding quantification of long-term outcomes on maternal and child health apart from breastfeeding initiation, and suggested that outcomes may differ substantially among poor and wealthy countries.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Additionally, the authors described potential negative outcomes associated with full implementation of the Baby Friendly Initiative, including promoting unrealistic breastfeeding expectations, mothers feeling pressured to breastfeed, and increased feelings of maternal guilt.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/baby-friendly-hospital-initiative] Further high quality studies were recommended to evaluate both long-term breastfeeding outcomes and other aspects of maternal health.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The **East India Company** (**EIC**) was an English, and later British, joint-stock company that was founded in 1600 and dissolved in 1874.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] It was formed to trade in the Indian Ocean region, initially with the East Indies (which included the Indian subcontinent and Southeast Asia), and later with East Asia.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The company gained control of large parts of the Indian subcontinent and Hong Kong.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] At its peak, the company was the largest corporation in the world by various measures and had its own armed forces in the form of the company's three presidency armies, totalling about 260,000 soldiers, twice the size of the British Army at certain times.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The company also initiated the beginnings of the British Raj in the Indian subcontinent.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The company eventually came to rule large areas of the Indian subcontinent, exercising military power and assuming administrative functions.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Under this government-like rule, the company used torture to extract taxes, reduced much of the population to poverty and enacted policies that resulted in the Great Bengal Famine of 1770, during which 10 million people starved to death.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Company-ruled areas in the region gradually expanded after the Battle of Plassey in 1757 and by 1858 most of modern India, Pakistan and Bangladesh, along with Lower Burma, was either ruled by the company or princely states closely tied to the company by treaties.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Following the Indian Rebellion of 1857, the Government of India Act 1858 led to the British Crown assuming direct control of present-day Bangladesh, India, Pakistan, and Myanmar in the form of the new British Raj.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The company subsequently experienced recurring problems with its finances, despite frequent government intervention.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The company was dissolved in 1874 under the terms of the East India Stock Dividend Redemption Act enacted one year earlier, as the Government of India Act had by then rendered it vestigial, powerless, and obsolete.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The official government machinery of the British Empire had assumed its governmental functions and absorbed its armies.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In 1577, Francis Drake set out on an expedition from England to plunder Spanish settlements in South America in search of gold and silver.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Sailing in the *Golden Hind* he achieved this, and then sailed across the Pacific Ocean in 1579, known then only to the Spanish and Portuguese.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Drake eventually sailed into the East Indies and came across the Moluccas, also known as the Spice Islands, and met Sultan Babullah.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In exchange for linen, gold, and silver, the English obtained a large haul of exotic spices, including cloves and nutmeg.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Drake returned to England in 1580 and became a hero; his circumnavigation raised an enormous amount of money for England's coffers, and investors received a return of some 5,000 percent.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Thus started an important element in the eastern design during the late sixteenth century.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] With England at war with Spain and Portugal in 1585 trade was now cut off, and Queen Elizabeth I resorted to privateering.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Soon after Thomas Cavendish's circumnavigation in 1587 and the Spanish Armada's defeat the following year, the captured Spanish and Portuguese ships and cargoes laid the foundation for further privateering to even more distant zones of the conflict.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] London merchants presented a petition to Elizabeth I for permission to sail to the Indian Ocean, and beyond with the Spice Islands of particular interest.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The aim was to deliver a decisive blow to the Spanish and Portuguese monopoly of far-eastern trade.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Elizabeth granted her permission and in 1591, James Lancaster in the *Bonaventure* with two other ships, financed by the Levant Company, sailed from England around the Cape of Good Hope to the Arabian Sea, becoming the first English expedition to reach India that way.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Having sailed around Cape Comorin to the Malay Peninsula, they preyed on Spanish and Portuguese ships there before returning to England in 1594.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The biggest prize that galvanised English trade was the seizure of a large Portuguese carrack, the *Madre de Deus*, by Walter Raleigh and the Earl of Cumberland at the Battle of Flores on 13 August 1592.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Equally valuable was the ship's rutter (mariner's handbook) containing vital information on the China, India, and Japan trade routes.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In 1596, three more English ships sailed east but all were lost at sea.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] A year later however saw the arrival of Ralph Fitch, an adventurer merchant who, with his companions, had made a remarkable nine year overland journey to Mesopotamia, the Persian Gulf, the Indian Ocean, India and Southeast Asia.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Fitch was consulted on Indian affairs and gave even more valuable information to Lancaster.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In 1599, a group of prominent merchants and explorers met to discuss a potential East Indies venture under a royal charter.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Besides Fitch the group included Stephen Soame, then Lord Mayor of London; Thomas Smythe, a powerful London politician and administrator; Richard Hakluyt, writer and proponent of English colonisation of the Americas; and several other sea-farers who had served with Drake and Raleigh.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] On 22 September, the group stated their intention "to venture in the pretended voyage to the East Indies (the which it may please the Lord to prosper)" and to themselves invest £30,133 (over £4,000,000 in today's money).
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Two days later, the "Adventurers" reconvened and resolved to apply to the Queen for support of the project.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Although their first attempt had not been completely successful, they sought the Queen's unofficial approval to continue.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] They bought ships for the venture and increased their investment to £68,373.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] She granted her charter to their corporation named **Governor and Company of Merchants of London trading into the East Indies**.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] For a period of fifteen years, the charter awarded the company a monopoly on English trade with all countries east of the Cape of Good Hope and west of the Straits of Magellan.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Any traders there without a licence from the company were liable to forfeiture of their ships and cargo (half of which would go to the Crown and half to the company), as well as imprisonment at the "royal pleasure".
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The charter named Thomas Smythe as the first governor of the company, and 24 directors (including James Lancaster) or "committees", who made up a Court of Directors.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] They, in turn, reported to a Court of Proprietors, who appointed them.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Ten committees reported to the Court of Directors.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] By tradition, business was initially transacted at the Nags Head Inn, opposite St Botolph's church in Bishopsgate, before moving to East India House on Leadenhall Street.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Sir James Lancaster commanded the first East India Company voyage in 1601 aboard *Red Dragon*.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The following year, whilst sailing in the Malacca Straits, Lancaster took the rich 1,200 ton Portuguese carrack *Sao Thome* carrying pepper and spices.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The booty enabled the voyagers to set up two "factories" (trading posts) – one at Bantam on Java and another in the Moluccas (Spice Islands) before leaving.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] On return to England in 1603, they learned of Elizabeth's death, but Lancaster was knighted by the new king, James I, on account of the voyage's success.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] By this time, the war with Spain had ended but the company had profitably breached the Spanish-Portuguese duopoly; new horizons opened for the English.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In March 1604, Sir Henry Middleton commanded the company's second voyage.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] General William Keeling, a captain during the second voyage, led the third voyage aboard *Red Dragon* from 1607 to 1610 along with *Hector* under Captain William Hawkins and *Consent* under Captain David Middleton.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Early in 1608, Alexander Sharpeigh was made captain of the company's *Ascension*, and general or commander of the fourth voyage.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Thereafter two ships, *Ascension* and *Union* (captained by Richard Rowles), sailed from Woolwich on 14 March 1608.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Initially, the company struggled in the spice trade because of competition from the Dutch East India Company.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] This rivalry led to military skirmishes, with each company establishing fortified trading posts, fleets, and alliances with local rulers.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The Dutch, better financed and supported by their government, gained the upper hand by establishing a stronghold in the spice islands (now Indonesia), enforcing a near-monopoly through aggressive policies that eventually drove the EIC to seek trade opportunities in India instead.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The English company opened a factory (trading post) in Bantam on Java on its first voyage, and imports of pepper from Java remained an important part of the company's trade for twenty years.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] English traders frequently fought their Dutch and Portuguese counterparts in the Indian Ocean.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The company achieved a major victory over the Portuguese in the Battle of Swally in 1612, at Suvali in Surat.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The company decided to explore the feasibility of a foothold in mainland India, with official sanction from both Britain and the Mughal Empire, and requested that the Crown launch a diplomatic mission.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Company ships docked at Surat in Gujarat in 1608.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The company's first Indian factory was established in 1611 at Masulipatnam on the Andhra Coast of the Bay of Bengal, and its second in 1615 at Surat.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The high profits reported by the company after landing in India initially prompted James I to grant subsidiary licences to other trading companies in England.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] However, in 1609, he renewed the East India Company's charter for an indefinite period, with the proviso that its privileges would be annulled if trade was unprofitable for three consecutive years.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In 1615, James I instructed Sir Thomas Roe to visit the Mughal Emperor Nur-ud-din Salim Jahangir (r.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] 1605–1627) to arrange for a commercial treaty that would give the company exclusive rights to reside and establish factories in Surat and other areas.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In return, the company offered to provide the Emperor with goods and rarities from the European market.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] — Nuruddin Salim Jahangir, Letter to James I.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The company, which benefited from the imperial patronage, soon expanded its commercial trading operations.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] It eclipsed the Portuguese Estado da Índia, which had established bases in Goa, Chittagong, and Bombay; Portugal later ceded Bombay to England as part of the dowry of Catherine of Braganza on her marriage to King Charles II.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The East India Company also launched a joint attack with the Dutch United East India Company (VOC) on Portuguese and Spanish ships off the coast of China that helped secure EIC ports in China, independently attacking the Portuguese in the Persian Gulf Residencies primarily for political reasons.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The company established trading posts in Surat (1619) and Madras (1639).
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] By 1647, the company had 23 factories and settlements in India, and 90 employees.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Many of the major factories became some of the most populated and commercially influential cities in Bengal, including the walled forts of Fort William in Bengal, Fort St George in Madras, and Bombay Castle.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] This compelled the company to formally abandon their efforts in the Spice Islands, and turn their attention to Bengal where, by this time, they were making steady, if less exciting, profits.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] What started as trading posts on undesirable land were developed into sprawling factory complexes with hundreds of workers sending exotic goods to England and managing protected points to export English finished goods to local merchants.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Throughout the entire century the company only resorted to force against the Mughals once, with terrible consequences.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The Anglo-Mughal war (1686–1690) was a complete defeat, ending when the EIC effectively swore fealty to the Mughals to get their factories back.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The East India Company's fortunes changed for the better in 1707 when Bengal and other regions under Mughal rule fell into anarchy after the death of the Mughal Emperor Aurangzeb.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] A series of large-scale rebellions, and the collapse of the Mughal taxation system led to the effective independence of virtually all of the pre-1707 Mughal fiefs and holdings, with their capital Delhi routinely under the control of Maratha, Afghan, or usurper generals' armies.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The EIC was able to take advantage of this chaos, slowly assuming direct control of the province of Bengal, and fighting numerous wars against the French for control of the east coast of the subcontinent.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The Company's position in the Mughal court as it fell apart made it possible to sponsor various powerful people on the subcontinent as they individually contended with others, steadily amassing more land and power in India to themselves.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In the 18th Century, the primary source of the Company's profits in Bengal became taxation in conquered and controlled provinces, as the factories became fortresses and administrative hubs for networks of tax collectors that expanded into enormous cities.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The Mughal Empire was the richest in the world in 1700, and the East India Company tried to strip it bare for a century thereafter.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Dalrymple calls it "the single largest transfer of wealth until the Nazis." What was in the 17th century the production capital of the world for textiles was forced to become a market for British-made textiles.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Statues, jewels, and various other valuables were moved from the palaces of Bengal to the townhouses of the English countryside.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Bengal in particular suffered the worst of Company tax farming, highlighted by the Great Bengal famine of 1770.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The primary tool of expansion for the company was the Sepoy.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The Sepoys were locally raised with European training and equipment, who changed warfare in present-day South Asia.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Mounted forces and their superior mobility had been king on the region's battlefields for a thousand years, with cannon so well integrated that the Mughals fought with cannon mounted on elephants; all were no match to line infantry with decent discipline supported with field cannon.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Repeatedly, a few thousand company sepoys fought vastly larger Mughal forces numerically and came out victorious.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Afghan, Mughal and Maratha factions started creating their own European-style forces, often with French equipment, as the chaos intensified and the stakes were raised.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Ultimately, the company won out, generally through as much diplomacy and state-craft as through fraud and deception.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] This relationship was repeatedly strained as the Company continued its expansion and exploitation, however it lasted in some form until 1858, when the last Mughal Emperor was exiled as the Company was disbanded and its assets were taken over by the British Crown.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In 1634, the Mughal emperor Shah Jahan extended his hospitality to English traders to Bengal, the richest region of the empire, and in 1717 customs duties were completely waived for the English in Bengal.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] By then, the Company's mainstay businesses were in cotton, silk, opium, indigo dye, saltpetre and tea.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Meanwhile, the Dutch, the Company's most aggressive competitors, had expanded their monopoly of the spice trade in the Straits of Malacca by ousting the Portuguese in 1640–1641.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] With reduced Portuguese and Spanish influence in the region, the EIC and VOC entered a period of intense competition, resulting in the Anglo-Dutch wars of the 17th and 18th centuries.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The British were also interested in trans-Himalayan trade routes, as they would create access to untapped markets for British manufactured goods in Tibet and China.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] This economic interest was showcased by the Anglo-Nepalese war (1814–1816).
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Within the first two decades of the 17th century, the Dutch East India Company or *Vereenigde Oostindische Compagnie* (VOC), was the wealthiest commercial operation in the world with 50,000 employees worldwide and a private fleet of 200 ships.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] It specialised in the spice trade and gave its shareholders 40% annual dividend.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The British East India Company was fiercely competitive with the Dutch and French throughout the 17th and 18th centuries over spices from the Spice Islands.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Some spices, at the time, could only be found on these islands, such as nutmeg and cloves; and they could bring profits as high as 400 per cent from one voyage.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The tension was so high between the Dutch and the British East Indies Trading Companies that it escalated into at least four Anglo-Dutch wars: 1652–1654, 1665–1667, 1672–1674 and 1780–1784.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Competition arose in 1635 when Charles I granted a trading licence to Sir William Courteen, which permitted the rival Courteen association to trade with the east at any location in which the EIC had no presence.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In 1689, a Mughal fleet commanded by Sidi Yaqub attacked Bombay.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] After a year of resistance the EIC surrendered in 1690, and the company sent envoys to Aurangzeb's camp to plead for a pardon.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The company's envoys had to prostrate themselves before the emperor, pay a large indemnity, and promise better behaviour in the future.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The emperor withdrew his troops, and the company subsequently re-established itself in Bombay and set up a new base in Calcutta.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The East India Company's archives suggest its involvement in the slave trade began in 1684, when a Captain Robert Knox was ordered to buy and transport 250 slaves from Madagascar to St.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The East India Company began using and transporting slaves in Asia and the Atlantic in the early 1620s, according to the Encyclopædia Britannica, or in 1621, according to Richard Allen.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Eventually, the company ended the trade in 1834 after numerous legal threats from the British state and the Royal Navy in the form of the West Africa Squadron, which discovered various ships had contained evidence of the illegal trade.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In 1613, during the rule of Tokugawa Hidetada of the Tokugawa shogunate, the British ship *Clove*, under the command of Captain John Saris, was the first English ship to call on Japan.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Unable to obtain Japanese raw silk for export to China, and with their trading area reduced to Hirado and Nagasaki from 1616 onwards, the company closed its factory in 1623.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The first of the Anglo-Indian wars occurred in 1686 when the company conducted naval operations against Shaista Khan, the governor of Mughal Bengal.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] This led to the siege of Bombay and the subsequent intervention of the Mughal Emperor, Aurangzeb.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Subsequently, the English company was defeated and fined.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In September 1695, Captain Henry Every, an English pirate on board the *Fancy*, reached the Straits of Bab-el-Mandeb, where he teamed up with five other pirate captains to make an attack on the Indian fleet returning from the annual pilgrimage to Mecca.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The Mughal convoy included the treasure-laden *Ganj-i-Sawai*, reported to be the greatest in the Mughal fleet and the largest ship operational in the Indian Ocean, and its escort, the *Fateh Muhammed*.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] They were spotted passing the straits en route to Surat.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The pirates gave chase and caught up with the *Fateh Muhammed* some days later, and meeting little resistance, took some £40,000 of silver.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Every continued in pursuit and managed to overhaul *Ganj-i-Sawai*, which resisted strongly before eventually striking.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] *Ganj-i-Sawai* carried enormous wealth and, according to contemporary East India Company sources, was carrying a relative of the Grand Mughal, though there is no evidence to suggest that it was his daughter and her retinue.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The loot from the *Ganj-i-Sawai* had a total value between £325,000 and £600,000, including 500,000 gold and silver pieces, and has become known as the richest ship ever taken by pirates.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] When the news arrived in England it caused an outcry.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] To appease Aurangzeb, the East India Company promised to pay all financial reparations, while Parliament declared the pirates *hostis humani generis* ("the enemy of humanity").
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In mid-1696 the government issued a £500 bounty on Every's head and offered a free pardon to any informer who disclosed his whereabouts.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The first worldwide manhunt in recorded history was underway.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The plunder of Aurangzeb's treasure ship had serious consequences for the English East India Company.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] To appease Emperor Aurangzeb and particularly his Grand Vizier Asad Khan, Parliament exempted Every from all of the Acts of Grace (pardons) and amnesties it would subsequently issue to other pirates.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The British began trading with China in 1699.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] This fact is recorded from the Chinese side in *The Draft History of the Qing* under the year Kangxi 37 (1698).
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The apparent discrepancy between the British and Chinese sources can be explained by the fact that Chinese New Year of 1699 did not fall until 31 January, so that any treaties entered into in January would have been logged under Kangxi 37 rather than Kangxi 38.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In 1715 the Company established a permanent "factory" in Guangzhou (Canton).
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The company started selling opium to Chinese merchants in the 1770s in exchange for goods like porcelain and tea, causing a series of opioid addiction outbreaks across China in 1820.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The ruling Qing dynasty outlawed the opium trade in 1796 and 1800, but British merchants continued illegally nonetheless.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The Qing took measures to prevent the East India Company from selling opium, and destroyed tens of thousands of chests of opium already in the country.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] This series of events led to the First Opium War in 1839, which involved a succession of British naval attacks along the Chinese coast over the course of several months.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] As part of the Treaty of Nanjing in 1842, the Qing were forced to give British merchants special treatment and the right to sell opium.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The Chinese also ceded territory to the British, including the island of Hong Kong.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The prosperity that the officers of the company enjoyed allowed them to return to Britain and establish sprawling estates and businesses, and to obtain political power, such as seats in the House of Commons.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Ship captains sold their appointments to successors for up to £500.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] As recruits aimed to return to Britain wealthy by securing Indian money, their loyalties to their homeland increased.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The company developed a lobby in the English parliament.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Pressure from ambitious tradesmen and former company associates (pejoratively termed *Interlopers* by the company), who wanted to establish private trading firms in India, led to the passing of the deregulating act in 1694.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] This act allowed any English firm to trade with India, unless specifically prohibited by act of parliament, thereby annulling the charter that had been in force for almost 100 years.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] When the **East India Company Act 1697** (9 Will.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] 44) was passed in 1697, a new "parallel" East India Company (officially titled the *English Company Trading to the East Indies*) was floated under a state-backed indemnity of £2 million.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The powerful stockholders of the old company quickly subscribed a sum of £315,000 in the new concern, and dominated the new body.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The two companies wrestled with each other for some time, both in England and in India, for a dominant share of the trade.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] It quickly became evident that, in practice, the original company faced scarcely any measurable competition.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The companies merged in 1708, by a tripartite indenture involving both companies and the state, with the charter and agreement for the new **United Company of Merchants of England Trading to the East Indies** being awarded by Sidney Godolphin, 1st Earl of Godolphin.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Under this arrangement, the merged company lent a sum of £3,200,000 to the Treasury, in return for exclusive privileges for the next three years, after which the situation was to be reviewed.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] A constant battle between the company lobby and Parliament followed for decades.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The company sought a permanent establishment, while Parliament would not willingly allow it greater autonomy and so relinquish the opportunity to exploit the company's profits.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In 1712, the **East India Company Act 1711** was passed, which renewed the status of the company, though the debts were repaid.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] By 1720, 15% of British imports were from India, almost all passing through the company, which reasserted the influence of the company lobby.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The licence was prolonged until 1766 by yet another act in 1730.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] At this time, Britain and France became bitter rivals.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Frequent skirmishes between them took place for control of colonial possessions.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In 1742, fearing the monetary consequences of a war, the British government agreed to extend the deadline for the licensed exclusive trade by the company in India until 1783, in return for a further loan of £1 million.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Between 1756 and 1763, the Seven Years' War diverted the state's attention towards consolidation and defence of its territorial possessions in Europe and its colonies in North America.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The war partly took place in the Indian theatre, between the company troops and the French forces.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In 1757, the Law Officers of the Crown delivered the Pratt–Yorke opinion distinguishing overseas territories acquired by right of conquest from those acquired by private treaty.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The opinion asserted that, while the Crown of Great Britain enjoyed sovereignty over both, only the property of the former was vested in the Crown.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] With the advent of the Industrial Revolution, Britain surged ahead of its European rivals.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Demand for Indian commodities was boosted by the need to sustain troops and the economy during the war, and by the increased availability of raw materials and efficient methods of production.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] As home to the revolution, Britain experienced higher standards of living.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Its ever-growing cycle of prosperity, demand and production had a profound influence on overseas trade.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The company became the single largest player in the British global market.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Sir John Banks, a businessman from Kent who negotiated an agreement between the king and the company, began his career in a syndicate arranging contracts for victualling the navy, an interest he kept up for most of his life.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] He knew that Samuel Pepys and John Evelyn had amassed a substantial fortune from the Levant and Indian trades.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Outstanding debts were also agreed and the company permitted to export 250 tons of saltpetre.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Again in 1673, Banks successfully negotiated another contract for 700 tons of saltpetre at £37,000 between the king and the company.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] So high was the demand from armed forces that the authorities sometimes turned a blind eye on the untaxed sales.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] One governor of the company was even reported as saying in 1864 that he would rather have the saltpetre made than the tax on salt.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The Seven Years' War (1756–1763) resulted in the defeat of the French forces, limited French imperial ambitions, and stunted the influence of the Industrial Revolution in French territories.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Robert Clive, the Governor-General, led the company to a victory against Joseph François Dupleix, the commander of the French forces in India, and recaptured Fort St George from the French.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The company took this respite to seize Manila in 1762.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] By the Treaty of Paris, France regained the five establishments captured by the British during the war (Pondichéry, Mahe, Karaikal, Yanam and Chandernagar) but was prevented from erecting fortifications and keeping troops in Bengal (art.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Elsewhere in India, the French were to remain a military threat, particularly during the War of American Independence, and up to the capture of Pondichéry in 1793 at the outset of the French Revolutionary Wars without any military presence.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Although these small outposts remained French possessions for the next two hundred years, French ambitions on Indian territories were effectively laid to rest, thus eliminating a major source of economic competition for the company.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In May 1772 the EIC stock price rose significantly.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In June Alexander Fordyce lost £300,000 shorting EIC stock, leaving his partners liable for an estimated £243,000 in debts.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] As this information became public, 20–30 banks across Europe collapsed during the British credit crisis of 1772–1773.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In India alone, the company had bill debts of £1.2 million.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] It seems that EIC directors James Cockburn and George Colebrooke were "bulling" the Amsterdam market during 1772.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The root of this crisis in relation to the East India Company came from the prediction by Isaac de Pinto that "peace conditions plus an abundance of money would push East Indian shares to exorbitant heights".
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] On 14 January 1773 the directors of the EIC asked for a government loan and unlimited access to the tea market in the American colonies, both of which were granted.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In August 1773 the Bank of England assisted the EIC with a loan.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The East India Company had also been granted competitive advantages over colonial American tea importers to sell tea from its colonies in Asia in American colonies.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] This led to the Boston Tea Party of 1773 in which protesters boarded British ships and threw the tea overboard.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] When protesters successfully prevented the unloading of tea in three other colonies and in Boston, Governor Thomas Hutchinson of the Province of Massachusetts Bay refused to allow the tea to be returned to Britain.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] This was one of the incidents which led to the American Revolution and independence of the American colonies.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The company's trade monopoly with India was abolished in the Charter Act 1813.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The monopoly with China was ended by the Saint Helena Act 1833 (3 & 4 Will.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] 85), ending the trading activities of the company and rendering its activities purely administrative.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In the aftermath of the Indian Rebellion of 1857 and under the provisions of the Government of India Act 1858, the British Government nationalised the company.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The British government took over its Indian possessions, its administrative powers and machinery, and its armed forces.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The company had already divested itself of its commercial trading assets in India in favour of the UK government in 1833, with the latter assuming the debts and obligations of the company, which were to be serviced and paid from tax revenue raised in India.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In return, the shareholders voted to accept an annual dividend of 10.5%, guaranteed for forty years, likewise to be funded from India, with a final pay-off to redeem outstanding shares.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The debt obligations continued beyond dissolution and were only extinguished by the UK government during the Second World War.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The company remained in existence in vestigial form, continuing to manage the tea trade on behalf of the British Government (and the supply of Saint Helena) until the East India Stock Dividend Redemption Act 1873 came into effect, on 1 January 1874.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] This act provided for the formal dissolution of the company on 1 June 1874, after a final dividend payment and the commutation or redemption of its stock.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The company's headquarters in London, from which much of India was governed, was East India House in Leadenhall Street.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] After occupying premises in Philpot Lane from 1600 to 1621; in Crosby House, Bishopsgate from 1621 to 1638; and in Leadenhall Street from 1638 to 1648, the company moved into Craven House, an Elizabethan mansion in Leadenhall Street.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The building had become known as East India House by 1661.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] It was completely rebuilt and enlarged in 1726–1729 and further significantly remodelled and expanded in 1796–1800.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] It was finally vacated in 1860 and demolished in 1861–1862.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The site is now occupied by the Lloyd's building.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In 1607, the company decided to build its own ships and leased a yard on the River Thames at Deptford.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] By 1614, the yard having become too small, an alternative site was acquired at Blackwall: the new yard was fully operational by 1617.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] It was sold in 1656, although for some years East India Company ships continued to be built and repaired there under the new owners.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In 1803 an act of Parliament, promoted by the East India Company, established the East India Dock Company, with the aim of establishing a new set of docks (the East India Docks) primarily for the use of ships trading with India.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The existing Brunswick Dock, part of the Blackwall Yard site, became the Export Dock; while a new Import Dock was built to the north.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In 1838 the East India Dock Company merged with the West India Dock Company.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The docks were taken over by the Port of London Authority in 1909 and closed in 1967.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The East India College was founded in 1806 as a training establishment for "writers" (i.e. clerks) in the company's service.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] It was initially located in Hertford Castle, but moved in 1809 to purpose-built premises at Hertford Heath, Hertfordshire.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In 1858 the college closed; but in 1862 the buildings reopened as a public school, now Haileybury and Imperial Service College.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The East India Company Military Seminary was founded in 1809 at Addiscombe, near Croydon, Surrey, to train young officers for service in the company's armies in India.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] It was based in Addiscombe Place, an early 18th-century mansion.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The government took it over in 1858 and renamed it the Royal Indian Military College.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In 1861 it was closed, and the site was subsequently redeveloped.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] In 1818, the company entered into an agreement by which those of its servants who were certified insane in India might be cared for at Pembroke House, Hackney, London, a private lunatic asylum run by Dr George Rees until 1838, and thereafter by Dr William Williams.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The arrangement outlasted the company itself, continuing until 1870, when the India Office opened its own asylum, the Royal India Asylum, at Hanwell, Middlesex.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The East India Club in London was formed in 1849 for officers of the company.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The Club still exists today as a private gentlemen's club with its club house situated at 16 St James's Square, London.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The English East India Company flag changed over time, with a canton based on the flag of the contemporary Kingdom, and a field of 9-to-13 alternating red and white stripes.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] From 1600, the canton consisted of a St George's Cross representing the Kingdom of England.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] With the Acts of Union 1707, the canton was changed to the new Union Flag—consisting of an English St George's Cross combined with a Scottish St Andrew's cross—representing the Kingdom of Great Britain.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] After the Acts of Union 1800 that joined Ireland with Great Britain to form the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland, the canton of the East India Company flag was altered accordingly to include a Saint Patrick's Saltire.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] There has been much debate about the number and order of stripes in the field of the flag.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Historical documents and paintings show variations from 9-to-13 stripes, with some images showing the top stripe red and others showing it white.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] At the time of the American Revolution the East India Company flag was nearly identical to the Continental Union Flag.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] Historian Charles Fawcett argued that the East India Company Flag inspired the Stars and Stripes of America.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The East India Company's original coat of arms was granted in 1600.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] When the East India Company was chartered in 1600, it was still customary for individual merchants or members of companies such as the Company of Merchant Adventurers to have a distinguishing merchant's mark which often included the mystical Sign of Four and served as a trademark.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] The East India Company's merchant mark consisted of a Sign of Four atop a heart within which was a saltire between the lower arms of which were the initials "EIC".
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p01] This mark was a central motif of the East India Company's coinage and forms the central emblem displayed on the Scinde Dawk postage stamps.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p02] Ships of the East India Company were called East Indiamen or simply "Indiamen".
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p02] Their names were sometimes prefixed with the initials "HCS", standing for "Honourable Company's Service" or "Honourable Company's Ship", such as HCS *Vestal* (1809) and HCS *Intrepid* (1780).
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p02] During the French Revolutionary and Napoleonic Wars, the East India Company arranged for letters of marque for its vessels such as *Lord Nelson*.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p02] This was not so that they could carry cannon to fend off warships, privateers, and pirates on their voyages to India and China (that they could do without permission) but so that, should they have the opportunity to take a prize, they could do so without being guilty of piracy.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p02] Similarly, *Earl of Mornington*, an East India Company packet ship of only six guns, also sailed under a letter of marque.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p02] In addition, the company had its own navy, the Bombay Marine, equipped with warships such as *Grappler*.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p02] These vessels often accompanied vessels of the Royal Navy on expeditions, such as the Invasion of Java.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p02] At the Battle of Pulo Aura, which was probably the company's most notable naval victory, Nathaniel Dance, Commodore of a convoy of Indiamen and sailing aboard the *Warley*, led several Indiamen in a skirmish with a French squadron, driving them off.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p02] On this occasion the Indiamen succeeded in bluffing their way to safety, and without any shots even being fired.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p02] Lastly, on 15 June 1795, *General Goddard* played a large role in the capture of seven Dutch East Indiamen off St Helena.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p02] East Indiamen were large and strongly built, and when the Royal Navy was desperate for vessels to escort merchant convoys, it bought several of them to convert to warships.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p02] *Earl of Mornington* became HMS *Drake*.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p02] Their design as merchant vessels meant that their performance in the warship role was underwhelming and the Navy converted them to transports.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p02] The amount of trade and shipping between Britain and company ports in India was considerable.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p02] For instance, in 1844, 534 ships (247,087 tons) arrived in Britain, and 540 vessels (239,368 tons) left UK ports for British India.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p02] Unlike all other British Government records, the records from the East India Company (and its successor the India Office) are not in The National Archives at Kew, London, but are held by the British Library in London as part of the Asia, Pacific and Africa Collections.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p02] The catalogue is searchable online in the *Access to Archives* catalogues.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p02] Many of the East India Company records are freely available online under an agreement that the Families in British India Society has with the British Library.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/british-east-india-company-p02] Published catalogues exist of East India Company ships' journals and logs, 1600–1834; accompanying catalogues also cover the company's daughter institutions, including the East India Company College, Haileybury, and Addiscombe Military Seminary.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Chalmers Hospital was founded by Alexander Chalmers (died 11 August 1835), a merchant of Banff, who left the whole of his estate to be applied, upon the death of his wife, towards funding and building a hospital for the people in the Royal Burgh of Banff.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Mrs Chalmers died in 1861, and Chalmers Hospital opened on 19 July 1864.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The original 'deed of mortification' set out that this was for any destitute sick persons born, domiciled or resident in the Banff area, although in 1929 the trustees successfully petitioned for the removal of this restriction.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Some major redevelopment work began in October 2008, after the hospital attracted criticism for not being up to date, with some of the interior features having been there since the Second World War.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The hospital remained open during the work, although the Findlater ward services were moved to Campbell Hospital in Portsoy until the Findlater ward was refurbished, and Seafield and Deveron ward were merged.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The midwifery unit was demolished and rebuilt to provide modern facilities.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Numerous other internal changes were also made inside, including X-ray facilities being moved to a different area of the building.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The redevelopment also provided upgraded facilities for physiotherapy, occupational therapy, speech and language therapy and podiatry.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The completion of the redevelopment was recognised with a visit by the Princess Royal in March 2012.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The hospital is supported by GPs from Banff, Gamrie, Deveron, Macduff, Portsoy and Aberchirder Medical Practices.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/dr-gray-s-hospital] The hospital was founded as a result of a bequest by Alexander Gray (d.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/dr-gray-s-hospital] 1807), who was born in Elgin but worked as a surgeon for the East India Company.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/dr-gray-s-hospital] His will was contested by his family, but eventually his bequest of £20,000 'for the establishment of a hospital in the town of Elgin for the sick and poor of the county of Murray (Moray)' was proven in the Court of Chancery.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/dr-gray-s-hospital] The hospital was designed by James Gillespie Graham, featuring a large classical block with giant Doric columns that supported a portico and was topped with drum tower and dome.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/dr-gray-s-hospital] Work on building the hospital at the western end of the town's High Street started in 1815 and the hospital opened on 1 January 1819, providing 30 beds that could be used for any parishioner of Moray who could produce a note of recommendation from their local minister of the established church.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/dr-gray-s-hospital] Often those of the Episcopalian or Catholic faith were turned away, causing conflict with the Burgh council on a number of occasions.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/dr-gray-s-hospital] Some patients who required urgent assistance were sent home critically ill lacking the paperwork from the Kirk minister, ultimately causing their death.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/dr-gray-s-hospital] A £22 million redevelopment of the hospital took place between 1992 and 1997 and included extensive refurbishment of existing facilities.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/dr-gray-s-hospital] The first stage, completed in May 1995, created a new complex for obstetrics, gynaecology and paediatric services, three new operating theatres and five new lifts.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/dr-gray-s-hospital] In January 1997 the second stage of redevelopment was completed, adding a new acute psychiatric ward and a new accident and emergency building.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/dr-gray-s-hospital] A sensory garden was opened in 2010 to provide patients, visitors and staff with an attractive place to relax.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/dr-gray-s-hospital] In 2012 a further £3 million redevelopment project commenced.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/dr-gray-s-hospital] The work, which included a new reception area, a rehabilitation ward, children's outpatient area and discharge lounge, was completed in 2013.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/dr-gray-s-hospital] Dr Gray's Hospital has 185 inpatient beds.
[src:dr-gray-s-hospital/dr-gray-s-hospital] It delivers approximately 1,100 births per year and has had full accreditation as baby friendly since May 2012.
